 <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 italic">Why are chargers getting smaller yet more powerful? The secret lies in Gallium Nitride (GaN). With the <strong><a href="https://commission.europa.eu/energy-climate-change-environment/standards-tools-and-labels/products-labelling-rules-and-requirements/sustainable-products/ecodesign-sustainable-products-regulation_en" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">EU Ecodesign Regulation (ESPR)</a> effective November 2025</strong> mandating standby power below 0.1W, a threshold many silicon designs cannot meet, GaN is rapidly becoming the only practical choice for new products. WOWOHCOOL explains why GaN is replacing silicon and how it benefits your tech ecosystem.</p>
 <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mt-4">The GaN fast-charging market is projected to reach approximately <strong>$12 billion in 2026</strong>, with GaN adoption growing <strong>41% year-over-year</strong>. GaN now accounts for an estimated <strong>40-50% of smartphone chargers at 65W and above</strong>, up from near zero just four years ago. As GaN power IC costs drop 8-12% annually, the technology is transitioning from premium niche to mainstream standard.</p>
