 <section id="how-gan-works" class="mb-16">
 <h2 class="text-2xl font-black text-brandBlue uppercase italic mb-6">6. How GaN Semiconductors Work</h2>
 <div class="bg-slate-50 rounded-2xl p-8">
 <p class="text-slate-600 mb-6">Understanding GaN technology doesn't require a degree in electrical engineering. Here's a simplified breakdown of how gallium nitride semiconductors revolutionize charging.</p>
 <div class="space-y-6">
 <div class="flex gap-4">
 <div class="w-10 h-10 bg-brandBlue rounded-full flex items-center justify-center text-white font-black shrink-0">1</div>
 <div>
 <h3 class="font-bold text-slate-900 mb-2">The Bandgap Advantage</h3>
 <p class="text-slate-600 text-sm">GaN has a bandgap of 3.4 eV compared to silicon's 1.1 eV. This fundamental property allows GaN devices to handle higher voltages and frequencies without breaking down. Think of it as the difference between a rubber band and a steel spring — one stretches and snaps, the other holds firm under pressure.</p>
 </div>
 </div>
 <div class="flex gap-4">
 <div class="w-10 h-10 bg-brandBlue rounded-full flex items-center justify-center text-white font-black shrink-0">2</div>
 <div>
 <h3 class="font-bold text-slate-900 mb-2">Faster Switching, Less Heat</h3>
 <p class="text-slate-600 text-sm">GaN transistors switch on and off up to 100x faster than silicon MOSFETs. This high-speed switching means energy spends less time in transition, resulting in minimal heat generation. The result: a charger that stays cool while delivering more power.</p>
 </div>
 </div>
 <div class="flex gap-4">
 <div class="w-10 h-10 bg-brandBlue rounded-full flex items-center justify-center text-white font-black shrink-0">3</div>
 <div>
 <h3 class="font-bold text-slate-900 mb-2">Higher Electron Mobility</h3>
 <p class="text-slate-600 text-sm">Electrons move through GaN material approximately 30% faster than in silicon. This translates to lower resistance and less energy lost as heat. In technical terms, GaN achieves this while maintaining a smaller die size — hence the compact charger designs we see today.</p>
 </div>
 </div>
 <div class="flex gap-4">
 <div class="w-10 h-10 bg-brandBlue rounded-full flex items-center justify-center text-white font-black shrink-0">4</div>
 <div>
 <h3 class="font-bold text-slate-900 mb-2">Zero Reverse Recovery Loss</h3>
 <p class="text-slate-600 text-sm">Unlike silicon diodes that experience "reverse recovery" losses when switching direction, GaN devices have negligible recovery losses. This is particularly beneficial in switched-mode power supplies where efficiency gains directly impact the charger's thermal performance.</p>
 </div>
 </div>
 </div>
 </div>
 <p class="text-slate-500 text-sm mt-4">According to <a href="https://www.transphorm.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-brandBlue hover:text-brandOrange">Transphorm</a>, one of the leading GaN power semiconductor manufacturers, GaN enables power conversion efficiency exceeding 99% in certain applications.</p>
 </section>
 <section id="gan-vs-sic" class="mb-16">
 <h2 class="text-2xl font-black text-brandBlue uppercase italic mb-6">7. GaN vs SiC (Silicon Carbide): Which Technology for Your Product?</h2>
 <p class="text-slate-600 mb-4">Silicon carbide (SiC) is another wide-bandgap semiconductor gaining traction in power electronics. While both GaN and SiC outperform traditional silicon, they target fundamentally different market segments. Understanding where each technology excels helps OEM buyers avoid over-engineering costs.</p>
 <p class="text-slate-600 mb-6"><strong>SiC in brief:</strong> Silicon carbide excels in high-voltage, high-power applications above 200W. It is the dominant technology in EV onboard chargers (6.6-22kW), industrial power supplies, and server PSUs. SiC wafers cost 3-5x more than GaN equivalents, making it impractical for consumer-priced accessories.</p>
