 </svg>GaN Chip Sourcing</h4>
 <p class="text-slate-600 text-sm">Major GaN chip suppliers include Navitas, GaN Systems (now acquired by STMicroelectronics), Texas Instruments, and Transphorm. Chinese manufacturers like Innosilicon also offer competitive alternatives. Chip availability can impact lead times — verify supply chain stability before placing large orders.</p>
 </div>
 </div>
 <div class="bg-brandBlue/10 border-l-4 border-brandBlue p-6 mt-6 rounded-r-xl">
 <h4 class="font-black text-brandBlue uppercase mb-2">Pro Tip</h4>
 <p class="text-slate-600 text-sm">Request "golden sample" verification before mass production. This physical sample serves as your quality benchmark and should match your specifications exactly. Document all specifications in a technical agreement to prevent disputes during production.</p>
 </div>
 </section>
 <section id="quality-checklist" class="mb-16">
 <h2 class="text-2xl font-black text-brandBlue uppercase italic mb-6">10. GaN Charger Quality Checklist</h2>
 <p class="text-slate-600 mb-6">Use this checklist when evaluating GaN charger suppliers or inspecting incoming shipments. A thorough quality verification process protects your brand reputation.</p>
 <div class="space-y-4">
 <div class="flex items-start gap-3 p-4 bg-slate-50 rounded-xl">
 <input type="checkbox" class="w-5 h-5 mt-1 accent-brandBlue">
 <div>
 <h4 class="font-bold text-slate-900">Efficiency Rating (95%+)</h4>
 <p class="text-slate-600 text-sm">Request efficiency test reports at various load levels (25%, 50%, 75%, 100%). The charger should maintain 95%+ efficiency across typical operating conditions.</p>
 </div>
 </div>
 <div class="flex items-start gap-3 p-4 bg-slate-50 rounded-xl">
 <input type="checkbox" class="w-5 h-5 mt-1 accent-brandBlue">
 <div>
 <h4 class="font-bold text-slate-900">Temperature Performance</h4>
 <p class="text-slate-600 text-sm">Test the charger at maximum rated load for 2+ hours. Surface temperature should remain below 60°C. Excessive heat indicates poor thermal design or substandard GaN chips.</p>
 </div>
 </div>
 <div class="flex items-start gap-3 p-4 bg-slate-50 rounded-xl">
 <input type="checkbox" class="w-5 h-5 mt-1 accent-brandBlue">
 <div>
 <h4 class="font-bold text-slate-900">Protocol Compatibility</h4>
 <p class="text-slate-600 text-sm">Verify support for required charging protocols: PD 3.0/3.1, PPS, QC4+/QC5.0, and proprietary protocols as needed. Test with actual devices that your customers will use.</p>
 </div>
 </div>
 <div class="flex items-start gap-3 p-4 bg-slate-50 rounded-xl">
 <input type="checkbox" class="w-5 h-5 mt-1 accent-brandBlue">
 <div>
 <h4 class="font-bold text-slate-900">Safety Certifications</h4>
 <p class="text-slate-600 text-sm">Confirm valid certificates: CE (Europe), FCC (USA), UL/cUL (North America), CCC (China). Verify certificate numbers against official databases to prevent counterfeit documentation.</p>
 </div>
 </div>
 <div class="flex items-start gap-3 p-4 bg-slate-50 rounded-xl">
 <input type="checkbox" class="w-5 h-5 mt-1 accent-brandBlue">
 <div>
 <h4 class="font-bold text-slate-900">Build Quality & Materials</h4>
 <p class="text-slate-600 text-sm">Inspect housing materials (should be fire-resistant PC/ABS), cable quality (braided or reinforced strain relief), and internal component brands. Request a teardown report for transparency.</p>
 </div>
 </div>
 <div class="flex items-start gap-3 p-4 bg-slate-50 rounded-xl">
 <input type="checkbox" class="w-5 h-5 mt-1 accent-brandBlue">
 <div>
 <h4 class="font-bold text-slate-900">EMI/EMC Compliance</h4>
 <p class="text-slate-600 text-sm">GaN chargers can produce electromagnetic interference if poorly designed. Ensure compliance with EN 55032 (EMC for multimedia equipment) and similar standards for your target markets.</p>
 </div>
 </div>
 <div class="flex items-start gap-3 p-4 bg-slate-50 rounded-xl">
 <input type="checkbox" class="w-5 h-5 mt-1 accent-brandBlue">
 <div>
 <h4 class="font-bold text-slate-900">Warranty Terms</h4>
 <p class="text-slate-600 text-sm">Negotiate minimum 12-month warranty with clear terms for defect replacement. Establish a defect rate threshold (typically 1-2%) for batch rejection or return policies.</p>
 </div>
 </div>
 </div>
 </section>
 <section id="future-developments" class="mb-16">
 <h2 class="text-2xl font-black text-brandBlue uppercase italic mb-6">11. Future GaN Developments</h2>
 <p class="text-slate-600 mb-6">The GaN technology roadmap shows continued innovation toward higher power, smaller size, and integrated solutions. Here's what to expect in the coming years.</p>
 <div class="grid md:grid-cols-3 gap-6 mb-8">
 <div class="bg-gradient-to-br from-brandBlue to-blue-800 rounded-xl p-6 text-white">
 <span class="text-xs font-black uppercase opacity-70">2025-2026</span>
 <h4 class="font-black text-xl uppercase mt-2 mb-3">150W-240W GaN</h4>
 <p class="text-sm opacity-80">Gaming laptops, professional workstations, and multi-device charging stations will see widespread GaN adoption at these power levels.</p>
 </div>
 <div class="bg-gradient-to-br from-brandOrange to-orange-600 rounded-xl p-6 text-white">
 <span class="text-xs font-black uppercase opacity-70">2027-2028</span>
 <h4 class="font-black text-xl uppercase mt-2 mb-3">GaN Integration</h4>
 <p class="text-sm opacity-80">System-on-chip integration combining controller, driver, and GaN transistor in single packages. Further size reductions of 30-40% expected.</p>
 </div>
 <div class="bg-gradient-to-br from-green-600 to-green-800 rounded-xl p-6 text-white">
 <span class="text-xs font-black uppercase opacity-70">2029+</span>
 <h4 class="font-black text-xl uppercase mt-2 mb-3">Universal GaN</h4>
 <p class="text-sm opacity-80">GaN becomes the default for all power conversion applications below 1kW, displacing silicon in consumer, industrial, and automotive markets.</p>
 </div>
 </div>
 <div class="bg-slate-50 rounded-xl p-6">
 <h4 class="font-black text-brandBlue uppercase mb-3"><svg class="icon-chart-line mr-2" aria-hidden="true" focusable="false" viewBox="0 0 512 512">
 <path d="M64 64c0-17.7-14.3-32-32-32S0 46.3 0 64L0 400c0 44.2 35.8 80 80 80l400 0c17.7 0 32-14.3 32-32s-14.3-32-32-32L80 416c-8.8 0-16-7.2-16-16L64 64zm406.6 86.6c12.5-12.5 12.5-32.8 0-45.3s-32.8-12.5-45.3 0L320 210.7 262.6 153.4c-12.5-12.5-32.8-12.5-45.3 0l-96 96c-12.5 12.5-12.5 32.8 0 45.3s32.8 12.5 45.3 0l73.4-73.4 57.4 57.4c12.5 12.5 32.8 12.5 45.3 0l128-128z" fill="currentColor"/>
 </svg>Market Projections</h4>
 <p class="text-slate-600 text-sm">According to market research from <a href="https://www.yolegroup.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-brandBlue hover:text-brandOrange">Yole Intelligence</a>, the GaN power device market is projected to reach $2B+ by 2028, with a 30%+ CAGR. Consumer chargers will remain the largest segment, followed by automotive and data center applications.</p>
 </div>
 </section>
